    <note>Dai(1) A [18666] The Yongjia Dai were clearly all members of the same root lineage and the connections between the separate branches may become clearer after CHECKing the funerary inscriptions authored by Dai(1) Xu [18685] in his Huanchuan ji. He was a lineage (third) nephew of Qi [18684] (q.v.), who was the son of Hou's [18674] (q.v.) elder cousin, and Xu authored the funerary inscription for Ruobing, who may be his father, but is recorded uncle until funerary inscription can be CHECKed. Shiyuan [18667], first Yongjia jinshi and his contemporary of Yuanxiu [18669], Hou's great grandfather, were the first mentioned Yongjia Dai(1). Tracing back the kinship distances from Xu, third nephew of Qi, and probable son or nephew of Ruobing, would make the unnamed grandfather of Shu [18670] and Xun(2) [18671], Dai A, as the father of Shiyuan and Yuanxiu and 6th generation ancestor of Xiongfei [18666], who would then be a third cousin of Ruobing and probable uncle of Meng [18682] and Zhi [18683]. I am treating A, Shu and Xun, and direct descendants, as members of jia 'a,' Yuanxiu and Shiyuan and their descendants as members of jia 'b,' and Xiongfei and his probable descendants as members of jia '.c.'</note>
